TI  - The dynamics of land use upon climate change: Projections from large-scale and family farming in Brazil
T2  - LAND USE POLICY
LA  - English
KW  - Climate change
KW  - Land use
KW  - Family farming
KW  - Large-scale farming
KW  - AGRICULTURE
AB  - The article analyzes the impacts of climate change on the pattern of land use in the macro-regions of Brazil, considering the productive specificities of large-scale and family farmers through the scenarios RCP 4.5 and RCP 8.5 (IPCC, 2014) between 2021 and 2050. The methodological strategy consists of the simultaneous estimation, via Iterated Seemingly Unrelated Regressions (ISUR), of a production function in which climatic, geographic, and productive factors determine the results in terms of land use change. The study contributes to the literature by disaggregating land use into large-scale and family farmers, indicating the magnitude and direction of the impacts by type of land use and by macro-region. The results indicate a higher sensitivity to changes in land use by large-scale farmers for crops and pastures. Deforestation by large-scale farmers is projected to increase in Brazil, with significant reductions in forest areas in the Midwest and South regions. Regarding family farming, forest areas could increase due to the reduction of crop and pasture areas. The study does not consider the overlap of areas between large-scale and family farmers so that the results may be overestimated. However, if there is an overlap, the climatic phenomenon may cause changes in the land structure.
