AB  - Alternatives to mitigate the impacts of climate change including the use of social enterprises (SEs) as a nexus between environmental, social, and economic challenges of soil salinity and drought are advocated. Within these views, we explored the role of SEs by examining their strengths in terms of knowledge and capacity, linkages, business performances, durability, and provision of ecosystem service to climate change. Two cases of SEs, the Quinoa Farming Women Cooperatives and Farmer Groups in Morocco and; the Malela and Mwendakulima Beekeepers in Tanzania were selected. The qualitative approach to inquire, collect, and analyse data was used. The cases positively contributed to addressing soil salinity and drought challenges through biodiversity restoration by pollination, afforestation, and alternative cropping. However, the strengths of SEs varied. Amid the climate advantages, SEs in the areas need to be strengthened to enhance sustained provision of the intended social and environmental values.
