TI  - Assessing resilience of surface water management schemes in Bangladesh: strategic insights for transformation
T2  - AQUA-WATER INFRASTRUCTURE ECOSYSTEMS AND SOCIETY
LA  - English
KW  - agricultural water management
KW  - coastal Bangladesh
KW  - policy implementation gaps
KW  - resilience assessment
KW  - transforming irrigation schemes
KW  - RISK
AB  - The sustainability of surface water management schemes (SWMSs) has become a key policy concern, particularly in terms of their resilience to climate change. Coastal hazards pose significant threats to SWMS infrastructure, such as canals and ponds, yet empirical evidence on their resilience remains limited. This study evaluates the resilience of SWMSs implemented under the Smallholder Agriculture Competitiveness Project in coastal Bangladesh. It also proposes strategies to enhance their long-term capacity. A novel framework was used to assess resilience, incorporating four risk management components - preparedness, mitigation, response, and recovery - across six development dimensions: social, economic, environmental, physical, institutional, and governance. Using 24 systematically developed indicators, a structured survey was conducted with 1,063 beneficiaries across 10 coastal districts. Results show that approximately half of the respondents perceive SWMS as moderately capable of anticipating, adapting to, and recovering from coastal hazards. A national-level participatory workshop identified five strategic directions, including short-, medium-, and long-term actions to transform SWMSs. Key policy recommendations include investing in climate-resilient irrigation infrastructure, addressing policy implementation gaps, mainstreaming gender, reforming water institutions, and promoting pond-based integrated farming systems.
AD  - Food & Agr Org United Nations, Dhaka, BangladeshAD  - Sher E Bangla Agr Univ, Dept Agr Extens & Informat Syst, Dhaka, BangladeshC3  - Food & Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO)C3  - Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University (SAU)FU  - Smallholder Agriculture Competitiveness Project (SACP) [UTF/BGD/068/BGD]; International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD)
FX  - The authors of the paper would like to thank the Smallholder Agriculture Competitiveness Project (SACP) (UTF/BGD/068/BGD), funded by the International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD) and the Government of Bangladesh, with technical assistance from FAO. SACP has been implementing various interventions, including SWMSs, to help smallholder farmers overcome the challenges of coastal hazards. Component 3 (Strengthen climate-resilient surface water management) of the SACP project provides supplemental or full-season irrigation access through various investments in irrigation water storage and delivery to agricultural land. These investments are accompanied by capacity development for groups and households to manage the irrigation infrastructure. The article focuses on four types of SWMS implemented by the Bangladesh Agriculture Development Corporation (BADC) with technical assistance from FAO within the project area - re-excavation and maintenance of canals, installation of buried pipe systems, crop protection dykes, and community ponds with homestead solar irrigation pumps. A brief description of these irrigation schemes is presented in Supplementary material 8.
