TI  - How misinformation and information asymmetry distort climate adaptation among smallholder farmers
T2  - AGRICULTURAL SYSTEMS
LA  - English
KW  - Climate change adaptation
KW  - Adoption of innovations
KW  - Smallholder farmers
KW  - Access to credit
KW  - Digital agriculture
KW  - Artificial intelligence (AI)
KW  - ICT-enabled advisory services
KW  - agricultural innovation systems
KW  - Agriculture 4.0
KW  - PROTECTION MOTIVATION
KW  - INSTITUTIONS
AB  - Context: Climate change poses escalating risks to smallholder agriculture, yet the effectiveness of adaptation depends not only on the availability of strategies but also on how farmers access, interpret, and trust information. In many rural contexts, misinformation and information asymmetry, particularly from market actors, shape decisions in ways that can undermine climate resilience and sustainability. Objective: This study investigates how misinformation and asymmetric information influence the adoption of climate change adaptation practices among smallholder farmers, using a Protection Motivation Theory (PMT) framework to link perceived risks, information credibility, and behavioral intent. It also situates these dynamics within broader debates on digital agriculture, Agriculture 4.0, and AI-based advisory systems, highlighting their dual role as both opportunities for innovation and channels of misinformation. Methods: The study was conducted in Upper Dir District, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, Pakistan, using a mixed-methods approach that combined a structured survey of 218 smallholder farmers with 22 in-depth qualitative interviews. Quantitative data were analyzed using a multivariate probit model, while qualitative data were thematically coded to contextualize statistical findings. Results and conclusions: The results indicated that borrowing inputs significantly reduced adoption of improved seeds, reflecting in-kind credit arrangements that lock farmers into market-controlled input choices. Exposure to asymmetric information in input markets increased adoption of gabion walls and agroforestry but reduced traditional stone bund use, indicating selective uptake driven by incomplete or biased advice. Weak public extension coverage forced farmers to rely on market vendors, who often provided commercially motivated guidance aimed at selling inputs rather than enhancing adaptive capacity. Access to credible online platforms significantly increased adoption of improved seeds, and traditional stone bunds, highlighting the potential of digital channels when reliable. Social media-based misinformation further reinforced existing information asymmetries and shaped farmers' decision-making environments. Significance: By foregrounding the role of information ecosystems in shaping adaptation behaviour, this study challenges linear, technocratic models of climate resilience. It underscores the need for governance approaches that regulate private information flows, strengthen public extension systems, and build trust-based, multi-stakeholder platforms for credible adaptation advice. In the era of digital agriculture, Agriculture 4.0, and AI-driven advisory tools, sustainable adaptation among smallholders will require not only technical solutions but also structural reforms to address the politics of information, power, and trust in rural agricultural systems.
