AB  - This study examines the challenges faced by farmers in the Western Himalayan Region (WHR) of India in adopting climate change adaptation strategies. Using a stratified random sampling technique, data were collected from 720 local farmers across various districts in the WHR. In order to address the climate change issues, the farmers of WHR have adopted to strategies such as crop rotation (99.9%), usage of fertilizers (96.25%), changing planting time (74.9%), using different crop varieties (58%) and using mixed cropping (31.8%). By utilizing the Problem Confrontation Index (PCI), the study identifies the primary barrier to climate change adaptation, which include raised farming costs (ranked 1st with a PCI score of 1975), inadequate irrigation facilities (ranked 2nd with a PCI score of 1429), and lack of access to money / credit facility (ranked 3rd with a PCI score of 1235). Additionally, these issues are exacerbated by a lack of information (PCI score of 694), insufficient water sources (PCI score of 539), and decreasing labour availability (PCI score of 340). The unique geography of the WHR, characterized by steep terrains, further complicates the adoption of certain adaptation strategies, such as farming near rivers or establishing regular irrigation systems. The study underscores the need for comprehensive solutions that address financial, infrastructural, and educational challenges to ensure sustainable farming practices in the WHR.
