AB  - Climate change and disaster shocks pose significant challenges to global agricultural sustainability and food security. Despite their crucial role, the effectiveness of government agricultural subsidies, a key policy instrument, remains insufficiently understood. Grounded in the Sustainable Livelihoods Framework (SLF), this study develops an extended model to investigate the complex interactions between disaster shock frequency, government subsidies, and farmers' livelihood strategies. Utilizing three waves of panel data (2014, 2016, and 2018) from 8,089 rural households across 586 villages in 25 Chinese provinces, drawn from the China Family Panel Studies (CFPS), we present three key findings: (1) Disaster shocks destabilize livelihoods, and prolonged exposure traps farmers in a "low-level dependency trap," impeding agricultural sustainability; (2) Government subsidies significantly improve the sustainability of agricultural livelihoods, although their effectiveness is moderated by the scale of agricultural production; and (3) Disaster frequency further complicates the relationship between subsidies, agricultural production scale, and livelihood outcomes. By clarifying the role of agricultural subsidies amid climate change and agrarian transition, this study provides strategic policy insights for reforming subsidy systems in the Global South.
