AB  - Adapting to climate variability is essential for sustainable livelihoods in developing countries like Ethiopia, where rainfed agriculture is vital. This study examines indigenous and introduced adaptation strategies across different agroecological zones, identifying the factors influencing their selection. Data were collected from 338 agricultural households using a questionnaire. The weighted average index (WAI) identified the main adaptation techniques, while the problem confrontation index (PCI) assessed barriers to effective adaptation. The multinomial logit model (MNL) analyzed the factors affecting adaptation choices. The results showed that indigenous methods like cultivating local crop varieties (WAI = 2.22), diversifying crops (WAI = 2.15), and adjusting planting dates (WAI = 2.14) were prevalent, while introduced strategies included using inorganic fertilizers (WAI = 2.64) and improved crop varieties (WAI = 2.41). Barriers such as limited farm size, lack of climate information, poor soil quality, and high input costs were identified through PCI. The MNL model highlighted education, access to credit, extension services, climate perception, and household income as key factors influencing adaptation strategies. These findings emphasize the need for region-specific interventions tailored to local environmental and socioeconomic conditions, which can help policymakers develop effective climate adaptation strategies that enhance resilience and sustainability in farming communities.
