TI  - Uprooting "Indigeneity" in South Africa's Western Cape: The Plant That Moves
T2  - AMERICAN ANTHROPOLOGIST
LA  - English
KW  - climate change
KW  - indigeneity
KW  - South Africa
KW  - precarity
KW  - place
KW  - CLIMATE-CHANGE
KW  - IDENTITY
KW  - CULTURE
AB  - Amid global concerns about climate change, scientists suggest that South African rooibos tea's indigenous ecosystem may be shifting southward. By 2011, rooibos farmers were beginning to worry that the plant was abandoning its proper home and undermining both their livelihoods and their rooted sense of belonging. Using the framework of plant and human mobility to explore the impact of environmental changes on one farming community, I investigate how climate change unsettles not only livelihoods but also social cosmologies. If rooibos's growing range shifts, how will it affect the ways that farmers understand and claim their heritage in connection to this indigenous plant? How does the uprooting of a plant's indigeneity influence ideas about cultural indigeneity as rooted in place? What role can anthropology play in theorizing ecological mobility? In addressing these questions, I contend that understanding the effects of climate change also involves destabilizing the idea of place. By focusing on plant mobility, I articulate a theory of geographical precarity: I imply that people's uncertain claims to belonging in place merged with uncertainty of the rootedness of place itself. I conclude by examining industry efforts to delineate and control where rooibos could legally grow through the creation of geographical indications.
