AB  - Conservation agriculture (CA) has been acknowledged as a sustainable way of farming that increases farmers' productivity, reduces their vulnerability, and mitigates the effects of climate change. However, the rate at which smallholder farmers in developing countries fully adopt CA is not impressive. This study investigated the factors associated with the adoption of conservation agriculture by smallholder farmers in the Mutasa District in Zimbabwe. Data was collected from 96 smallholder farmers. The study employed a cross-sectional research design and a quantitative approach. An ordered logistic regression was used to determine the factors associated with smallholder farmers' decision to adopt CA practices, measured across four ordered levels. The results show that only 10% of the farmers fully embraced all three principles of CA. The regression results indicated that non-agricultural work, receiving remittances, education level, and receiving agricultural training had a significant relationship with the adoption of conservation agriculture practices. The study recommends that farmers take advantage of the training programs on conservation agriculture brought to them by extension workers and various NGOs. There is a need for policymakers and NGOs to promote diversified non-farming income sources for farmers in areas where CA practices are underutilised, as evidence suggests that smallholder farmers' engagement in non-agricultural work enhances adoption.
