AB  - This study assessed farmers' local knowledge of climate variability and its link to climatic data in Ngoma District using rainfall and temperature data for the 1983-2021 period obtained from the Rwanda Meteorology Agency, with survey responses gathered from 400 farmers. Trend analysis at alpha = 95% was computed using the Modified Mann-Kendall (MMK) test and Sen's slope estimator. The Results indicated a statistically significant decrease in the diurnal temperature range (DTR) at rates of - 0.0345 degrees C/year during MAM and - 0.02657 degrees C/year during SOND. For both MAM and SOND seasons, mean temperature (T) and minimum temperature (Tn) increased by 0.0115 degrees C/year and 0.014 degrees C/year (T) and by 0.023 degrees C/year and 0.021 degrees C/year (Tn), respectively. Conversely, maximum temperature (Tx) exhibited decreasing trends of -0.0114 degrees C/year (MAM) and - 0.007 degrees C/year (SOND). The onset date (OD) ranges between February 9 and April 9 for MAM, and between September 7 and November 26 for SOND. The cessation date (CD) ranges from June 2 to 12 during MAM and from December 29 to January 12 during SOND. There are both similarities and differences between local knowledge and climate data. Most respondents (63% for MAM and 84% for SOND) are unaware of the onset of the seasons. The Majority of farmers (99%) indicate that SOND last longer than usual while 83% indicate that MAM starts later than usual. Furthermore, nearly all (97%) are aware of the information disseminated by Meteo-Rwanda. The data confirmed significant farmer perceptions, including increased rainfall intensity, irregular seasonal patterns, and shifts in precipitation dynamics. Enhancing farmers' knowledge and accessibility to diverse climate information would support agricultural management and planning, thereby boosting agricultural productivity.
